(1, 1, '2017-10-04 05:39:47', '2017-10-04 05:39:47', 'Social networks are built on the simple premise that any user can publish a singular statement. And while you can challenge the person on their message or view you canât really have a constructive debate. Social media services just arenât set up for debate. And as a result, any time you try to debate a statement in a social platform, the discussion becomes contentious and rarely reaches a conclusion. \r\n\r\nAs a reaction to the resulting cacophony that has grown as a result of the quazi-debate phenomenon living in the com\r\nments of social posts, we have spent the past four years working to deliver a social service that could more effectively facilitate debate.\r\n \r\nWhat we have found is that the answer is the question. From sports to pop culture, we have consistently seen that topical enthusiasts love answering questions, reading answers to questions, and picking sides. Consistent with the values of the age-old debate rules used from high schools to national political elections, a question provides the framing for debate that allows for two individuals to take sides and argue for their side. And it allows spectators to align to one side or the other of the argument to determine a winnerâa conclusion. \r\n\r\nAnd conclusions matter. \r\n\r\nMore than ever before, we are living in a sound bite culture with endless opinions and no easy way to align. No way to find consensus. No way to understand how to associate. Conclusions allow the winner, loser, and followers to formally close the issue. It allows people to gain credibility the more they win and allows people to find affinity groups from like views. ', 'Questions Center Social Discourse', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hello-world', '', '', '2017-10-05 10:51:59', '2017-10-05 10:51:59', '', 0, 'http://202.164.49.132:4259/sidemarketing/?p=1', 0, 'post', '', 2),
(25, 1, '2017-02-09 10:03:14', '2017-02-09 10:03:14', 'Nielson recently produced a report on the state of radio as a marketing channel concluding that there is that evidence that money spent on radio is money well spent. With their single source purchaser data capability they are able to determine marketing effectiveness in radio. Sounds great but expensive. Canât we just ask our listeners directly?', 'Reaching Listener-Level Measurement in Radio', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '1914-translation-by-h-rackham', '', '', '2017-10-04 12:25:19', '2017-10-04 12:25:19', '', 0, 'http://shapeux.com/wp/theme/dodge/?p=25', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(29, 1, '2017-02-09 10:05:09', '2017-02-09 10:05:09', 'Iâve spent my career on the radio. In the 90s and early 2000s, the industry was vibrant and growing. Radio host and their producers just made content and all was well. But then digital happened and everything became measurable except for radio. And for the last decade, we have seen margins erode as we saw ad dollars migrate to more measureable chan\r\n-', 'Radio Relations', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'these-cases-are-perfectly-simple', '', '', '2017-10-04 12:23:48', '2017-10-04 12:23:48', '', 0, 'http://shapeux.com/wp/theme/dodge/?p=29', 0, 'post', '', 0),
